<TITLE> Indo-Bangla jt project to save tigers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 26 (bdnews24.com) -- Bangladesh and India are launching a project to develop the Sundarbans and save nearly extinct Royal Bengal Tigers and other wildlives. State minister for environment Hasan Mahmud said that World Bank has offered to fund the joint endeavour. He said steps would be taken after the Bank talks with the Indian authorities. The state minister spoke to reporters after a visit by a delegation led by the Bank's resident representative Allen Goldstein to discuss their 'Global Tiger Initiative' at his office on Wednesday. He said the Bank will finance the project. Currently it is funding a project to develop the forest on the India side. They are also undertaking a project titled 'Pilot Project for Climate Resilience (PPCR)' at the 12 coastal districts, the junior minster added. Under it, one large embankment will be built at every district to save the coastal environment and save people from calamities, Mahmud added. Around Tk 840 crores will be spent on its implementation. Nearly half the allocation will come in grants or cash assistance. The rest would be funded by the World Bank. The Bank will also take Asian Development Bank's support. b
